posts.post_content:
@endersblade  

[Counterspell](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Counterspell) isn't 'strictly better' than [Cancel](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Cancel), I really with you people would stop saying that.  

It's situational. The most obvious would be if you're playing a deck that works around transmute and other CMC 3 cards, you'd want to be able to tutor for this with your [Drift of Phantasms](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Drift of Phantasms).

@ifegainwithbite  
Yes, [Counterspell](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Counterspell ) is better than [Cancel](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Cancel) 99.9% of the time. However, it is not *strictly* better... sometimes having a higher CMC is beneficial, as in the case of transmute cards, [counterbalance](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=counterbalance), [spellbound dragon](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=spellbound dragon), and so on.   

Seriously, people, learn what the words "strictly better" means. See [Shock](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Shock) vs [Lightning Bolt](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Lightning Bolt). where the only time that you would want shock over LB is if your opponent plays [Meddling Mage](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Meddling Mage ) and names Lightning bolt. Same with [Greatsword](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Greatsword ) vs [Vulshok Battlegear](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Vulshok Battlegear)

